    <!-- MAIN -->
    <div class="docs-main">
      <span class="docs-kicker">Documentation</span>
      <h1>Get started with Tasca</h1>
      <p class="docs-lead">Everything you need to get a board running where humans and AI agents work the same tickets — hosted by us, with your repos, your keys, and your models.</p>

      <section class="docs-sec" id="overview">
        <h2>Overview</h2>
        <p>Tasca is a managed, multi-tenant delivery platform. It runs on Postgres, talks to the coding agents you already use, and routes every ticket to whoever — human or agent — can actually complete it. We host and operate the platform; you connect your repos and models.</p>
        <p>Three pieces make that work:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><b style="color:var(--fg-2)">Complexity tiers</b> — every ticket carries a tier from <span class="kbd">basic</span> to <span class="kbd">ultra</span> that describes how much reasoning it needs.</li>
          <li><b style="color:var(--fg-2)">Agents</b> — each agent declares the tiers it can take, where it runs, and how many sessions it handles at once.</li>
          <li><b style="color:var(--fg-2)">The assignment engine</b> — a deterministic <span class="kbd">decide()</span> that matches ready work to a capable, free agent and prompts it the way that agent needs.</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="note"><div class="nh">Heads up</div><p>This guide covers the hosted service. Prefer to run Tasca on your own infrastructure? Jump to <a href="#self-host">Self-host</a> — it's open source under Apache-2.0.</p></div>
      </section>

      <section class="docs-sec" id="get-started">
        <h2>Create a workspace</h2>
        <p>Hosted Tasca takes a few minutes to start — there's no infrastructure to provision. We run the server, the Postgres database, realtime sync, and execution sandboxing for you.</p>
        <h3>The first five minutes</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Create your organization and invite your team.</li>
          <li>Connect a GitHub repo through the Tasca GitHub App.</li>
          <li>Add your model providers, and optionally a local model endpoint over the network.</li>
          <li>Tier your first tickets and let routing dispatch them to a capable agent.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Your org's keys and secrets are encrypted at rest under a dedicated key. We never train on your data, and you can export or delete it at any time — see the <a href="/security">security model</a> for the full picture.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="docs-sec" id="add-agent">
        <h2>Add an agent</h2>
        <p>An agent is any executor profile plus a capability declaration. Point one at a local model over the network, or at a cloud provider with its own credential.</p>
        <h3>Local model via Ollama</h3>
        <div class="code"><span class="cm"># a headless Mac running qwen3-coder, reachable on your tailnet</span>
tasca agent add qwen3-coder \
  <span class="tk">--executor</span> qwen \
  <span class="tk">--base-url</span> http://m1max.tailnet:11434 \
  <span class="tk">--min-tier</span> basic <span class="tk">--max-tier</span> medium \
  <span class="tk">--concurrency</span> 1</div>
        <p>The single GPU serializes inference, so local agents default to <span class="kbd">concurrency_limit=1</span>. Tasca's atomic claim guarantees two dispatchers never over-commit the same agent.</p>
        <h3>Cloud Claude for hard work</h3>
        <div class="code"><span class="cm"># cloud agent carries its own key, isolated for cost attribution</span>
tasca agent add claude-sonnet \
  <span class="tk">--executor</span> claude-code \
  <span class="tk">--credential</span> anthropic:worker \
  <span class="tk">--min-tier</span> medium <span class="tk">--max-tier</span> ultra</div>
        <p>Worker credentials stay separate from the org's PM-assistant key, so model spend is attributed and rate-limited per agent.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="docs-sec" id="self-host">
        <h2>Self-host (optional)</h2>
        <p>Prefer to run Tasca on your own infrastructure? The full platform is open source under Apache-2.0 — you trade the managed conveniences for complete control, and the product is identical either way. It ships as a Docker Compose stack: the server, a Postgres database with logical replication, and the realtime sync service. No closed cloud relay, no telemetry.</p>
        <h3>Requirements</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Docker and Docker Compose</li>
          <li>Postgres 15+ with <span class="kbd">wal_level=logical</span> (provisioned by the stack)</li>
          <li>A reverse proxy terminating TLS (a sample <span class="kbd">Caddyfile</span> is included)</li>
        </ul>
        <h3>Bring up the stack</h3>
        <div class="code"><span class="cm"># clone and start</span>
git clone <span class="tk">github.com/icemint/tasca</span>
cd tasca
cp .env.example .env   <span class="cm"># set SERVER_ENCRYPTION_KEY + JWT secret</span>
docker compose up <span class="tk">-d</span></div>
        <p>The server comes up on <span class="kbd">:8080</span>. On first login the bootstrap operator account is seeded from your env secret; after that, credentials are per-user and argon2id-hashed.</p>
        <div class="note"><div class="nh">Secrets</div><p>Set a dedicated <span class="kbd">SERVER_ENCRYPTION_KEY</span>. Stored secrets (org API keys, reset tokens) are encrypted with it — independently of the JWT secret — so rotating JWTs never locks out stored keys.</p></div>
      </section>

      <section class="docs-sec" id="tiers">
        <h2>Complexity tiers</h2>
        <p>The tier encodes how decomposed a ticket must be before an agent may pick it up. Lower tiers demand more up-front structure; higher tiers allow — and require — more reasoning.</p>
        <table class="tier-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Tier</th><th>Required before pickup</th><th>Typical owner</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><span class="tier tier-basic"><span class="dot"></span>Basic</span></td><td>Exact files, explicit IO contract, acceptance gate, every edge case enumerated.</td><td><span class="handler local">Local</span></td></tr>
            <tr><td><span class="tier tier-low"><span class="dot"></span>Low</span></td><td>+ affected modules and a constrained tool list.</td><td><span class="handler local">Local</span></td></tr>
            <tr><td><span class="tier tier-medium"><span class="dot"></span>Medium</span></td><td>+ a design note. Reasoning allowed.</td><td><span class="handler local">Local</span> <span class="handler cloud">Cloud</span></td></tr>
            <tr><td><span class="tier tier-hard"><span class="dot"></span>Hard</span></td><td>+ a human-authored plan. Cloud recommended.</td><td><span class="handler cloud">Cloud</span></td></tr>
            <tr><td><span class="tier tier-ultra"><span class="dot"></span>Ultra</span></td><td>Human owns it; the agent assists, doesn't drive.</td><td><span class="handler human">Human</span></td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>Validation blocks <span class="kbd">start</span> if the required fields for a ticket's tier are missing, and hands back a checklist of exactly what's absent. Raise a tier later and previously-satisfied fields are retained — only the newly-required ones are prompted.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="docs-sec" id="routing">
        <h2>Capability routing</h2>
        <p>When a ticket starts, the assignment engine selects an agent with a single, side-effect-free decision:</p>
        <div class="code">min_tier ≤ <span class="tk">issue.tier</span> ≤ max_tier
  <span class="pr">AND</span> availability = <span class="tk">free</span>
  <span class="pr">AND</span> active_sessions &lt; concurrency_limit
  <span class="pr">AND</span> issue is unassigned
  <span class="pr">AND</span> not blocked by an open relationship
  <span class="pr">AND</span> in the active sprint</div>
        <p>The decision is one of five outcomes — never a silent no-op:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><b style="color:var(--fg-2)">Assigned</b> — claim the agent, seed the session with its config.</li>
          <li><b style="color:var(--fg-2)">Queued</b> — all capable agents busy; FIFO by priority, picked up on release.</li>
          <li><b style="color:var(--fg-2)">No capable agent</b> — ticket stays put, flagged, leads notified.</li>
          <li><b style="color:var(--fg-2)">Blocked</b> — an open blocking relationship stops dispatch.</li>
          <li><b style="color:var(--fg-2)">Manual override</b> — an explicit executor wins, tagged for audit.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>A failed attempt never auto-escalates. It flips the ticket to <span class="kbd">needs_attention</span> with the reason and offers a one-click bump to the next tier or a cloud agent.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="docs-sec" id="scaffolding">
        <h2>Prompt scaffolding</h2>
        <p>Each tier wraps the ticket prompt in a versioned, per-org template. Basic and low templates constrain the tool surface, cap <span class="kbd">max_turns</span>, and forbid open-ended planning — implement exactly the spec, don't redesign. Higher tiers relax those guards.</p>
        <p>Templates are editable and versioned, so an org can pin or upgrade independently. Saving a template that references a tool an agent lacks warns at save time, not at runtime.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="docs-sec" id="github">
        <h2>GitHub automation</h2>
        <p>Connect a project to one or more repos through the GitHub App. When an agent opens a PR on the ticket's branch, it links back automatically and review events move the ticket:</p>
        <div class="rules" style="margin-top:18px">
          <div class="rule"><span class="from">PR opened</span><span class="arrow">→</span><span class="status-badge sb-review">In review</span></div>
          <div class="rule"><span class="from">changes_requested</span><span class="arrow">→</span><span class="status-badge sb-changes" style="background:color-mix(in srgb,var(--red) 13%,transparent)">Ready for dev</span></div>
          <div class="rule"><span class="from">approved</span><span class="arrow">→</span><span class="status-badge sb-approved">Ready to merge</span></div>
          <div class="rule"><span class="from">merged</span><span class="arrow">→</span><span class="status-badge sb-merged">Done</span></div>
        </div>
        <p>Transitions are event-sourced on PR state and idempotent, so duplicate or out-of-order webhooks converge to the right status. A reconciliation poller catches anything a missed webhook would have dropped.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="docs-sec" id="security">
        <h2>Security &amp; roles</h2>
        <p>Tasca ships four roles. The propose-only guest tier exists so external clients can file work without ever triggering execution.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><b style="color:var(--fg-2)">Owner</b> — billing, org keys, delete org.</li>
          <li><b style="color:var(--fg-2)">Admin</b> — members, projects, agents, sprints, org key.</li>
          <li><b style="color:var(--fg-2)">Member</b> — create and assign tickets, review PRs, run agents.</li>
          <li><b style="color:var(--fg-2)">Guest</b> — propose-only: file and comment, never execute.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Any external-touch execution runs in an ephemeral sandbox with no host filesystem, no secrets, and restricted egress. See the full <a href="/security">security model</a> for the threat model and isolation guarantees.</p>
      </section>
    </div>

    <!-- TOC -->
    <aside class="docs-toc" aria-label="On this page">
